Phalonidia affinitana, the large saltmarsh conch, is a species of moth of the family Tortricidae. It is found in China (Liaoning, Tianjin, Xinjiang), Japan, Korea, Russia and most of Europe. The habitat consists of salt marshes.The wingspan is 11â€“14 mm.The forewings are elongate and the costa gently arched. The  ground colour is light brownish-ochreous, submetallic and strigulated with fuscous. There is a slender straight brownish antemedian fascia parallel to the termen and interrupted beneath the costa and a dark fuscous dorsal dot or small spot before the tornus. The hindwings are grey.The larva is whitish, dorsally greyish - tinged ; spiracular line faint, grey ; head brown ; plate of 2 blackAdults are on wing from June to August in western Europe.
The larvae feed on the flowers of Aster tripolium. Larva can be found feeding on the flowers from July to August. In September, they bore down the flower stalk and stem to the rootstock. It overwinters in the roots and pupates in March, either in the roots or in debris.